Land use and cover maps were created using Landsat OLI images from 2015 to 2023, with 89.9% and 98.8% accuracy. The study area has diverse land-use classes, influenced by the Nile River proximity and industrial, agricultural, and urban activities. The classification of land into cultivated, built-up, water bodies, and barren land is based on land use and cover, with areas dominated by agricultural and industrial activities being considered anthropogenic sources for water and environmental hazard change, (Fig. 3
                        ). Changing maps between 2015 and 2023, cultivated land dominated the study area, except for western desert fringes, which increased by 13.74% with an area of about 334.87 Km2. This increase is primarily due to reclamation projects in the area, which contribute to surface and groundwater potentiality due to irrigation. The study reveals a decrease in barren lands by 37.32% with an area of about 5962.3 Km2, largely due to urban development and reclamation projects, which increased water pollution and change from wastewater discharge into surface and groundwater resources (Elbeih and El-Zeiny 2018). The Nile River and other water bodies in land use/cover maps have decreased by 8.46% with an area of about 12.66 Km2%, and other increased with urban in land use/cover maps by 28.28% with an area of about 173.85 Km2% due to land reclamation processes. The large area of urban and cultivated lands with time increases environmental risks (Fig. 3), and (Table .1
                        ).
